[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 7: Cache invalidation during terminology updates.** When you load a new terminology version into Neptune, your Redis cache holds stale mappings. The naive approach (flush everything) causes a thundering herd of cache misses against Neptune. The smart approach computes what changed and selectively invalidates only the affected keys. For large annual updates (like the yearly ICD-10-CM release that changes thousands of codes), selective invalidation can still be massive, so you need a threshold above which you flush the entire cache and optionally run a cache warming step for the most frequently queried concepts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION invalidate_cache_after_load(terminology_name, old_version, new_version):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute the delta: which concept codes changed between versions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // "Changed" means added, retired, or had relationships modified.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The terminology release notes typically include a changes file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (e.g., ICD-10-CM provides an addendum with new/revised/deleted codes).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     changed_codes = compute_terminology_delta(terminology_name, old_version, new_version)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define a threshold for switching between selective and full invalidation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If more than 10% of cached concepts changed, it's cheaper to flush everything
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // than to issue thousands of individual DELETE commands.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SELECTIVE_THRESHOLD = 5000
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF length(changed_codes) > SELECTIVE_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Large delta (e.g., annual ICD-10 update). Flush the entire cache.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         redis.flushdb()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Optionally warm the cache for the top-N most queried concepts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Pull top queries from CloudWatch Logs Insights or a separate counter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         top_concepts = get_top_queried_concepts(limit=1000)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each concept in top_concepts:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             normalize_concept(concept.code, concept.terminology)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Each call populates the cache as a side effect.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Small delta (e.g., monthly RxNorm update with a few hundred changes).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Selectively delete cache keys for changed concepts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each code in changed_codes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Delete all cache keys that reference this code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Cache keys follow the pattern: norm:{terminology}:{code}:{targets}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Use a SCAN + match pattern rather than KEYS (KEYS blocks Redis).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             pattern = "norm:" + terminology_name + ":" + code + ":*"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             matching_keys = redis.scan_match(pattern)
